**"What is Olist?"**
Brazil's largest e-commerce marketplace — like Amazon but for Brazil. The dataset is real public data from 2016-2018.

---

**"What datasets did you use?"**
3 CSVs — orders (99K rows), order items (112K rows), and reviews (100K rows). Joined them on order_id to build the master dataset.

---

**"What did you build in Streamlit?"**
6-page dashboard — Overview KPIs, Order Funnel, Revenue trends, Delivery performance, Reviews & NPS, and Cohort analysis. Added sidebar filters for month and order status.

---

**"What is NPS and how did you calculate it?"**
Net Promoter Score. Promoters = review score 5, Detractors = score 1-2. Formula: (Promoters% - Detractors%) = 42.3. Means more happy customers than unhappy ones.

---

**"What was your key insight?"**
Late deliveries get 0.6 points lower review scores on average. Orders delivered in 0-7 days score ~4.4, orders taking 30+ days score ~3.8. Directly links operations to customer satisfaction.

---

**"What SQL did you write?"**
15 queries — window functions for funnel percentages, CTEs for NPS calculation, JOINs across 3 tables for revenue, DATE_TRUNC for monthly cohorts, CASE WHEN for delivery buckets.

---

**"What is analysis.py?"**
It's the analytics engine — all calculation logic lives there as separate functions (kpis, order_funnel, delivery_analysis, nps, etc.). Both app.py and charts.py import from it so the logic isn't duplicated.

---

**"What is charts.py?"**
Exports all charts as PNG files — useful for putting into PowerPoint or sharing with stakeholders who don't have Streamlit running.

